<br>
Enchanters <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> die</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> while charm soloing (until they have Dire Charm)... that's the whole point.  Unless they go somewhere with a pathing bug (OOT or Oasis, for example) or have 3rd party buffs, the risk of charm soloing is outrageously high.  <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> That is the difference between the charm line of spells and magician pets!</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  <br>
<br>
At least Krilen understands that.<br>
<br>
But back to the point.  Supposedly we're getting a bunch of people from both classes to do this, right?  So, theoretically, a somewhat large sample size with normalize the results, right?  Sure, if one person from class_x dies 10 times, that doesn't mean much.  But if 15 of 20 people die 10 times, and the other 5 die twice, compared to 3 of 20 from class_y, there's a fairly significant difference.<br>
<br>
Does lag have an effect on charm soloing?  Absolutely.  A huge effect.  One bad spike, and you can have 2+ mobs on you... instead of one on you and a dead pet.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The 50% exp penalty only applies to the mage...<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Um... if the enchanter has a Memory from Exiled, I'll agree with that.  Otherwise, attempting to outdamage, or blur-outdamage the pet is both extremely mana inefficient and extremely unreliable.<br>
<br>
